.TH IMGMOD-COLLAGE 1 "July 9, 2026" "imgmod 1.4.1"
.SH NAME
imgmod-collage \- Stitch multiple images together
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B imgmod collage
[\fB-H\fR|\fB-V\fR] [\fB-o\fR \fIOUTPUT\fR] \fIINPUT\fR [\fIINPUT ...\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B imgmod collage
uses ImageMagick to stitch multiple images together without padding.

Inputs can be image files or directories. Directories are searched recursively,
and discovered files are processed in sorted order within each directory.

Vertical collages scale images down to the smallest input width before
stitching. Horizontal collages scale images down to the smallest input height
before stitching.

When \fIOUTPUT\fR is omitted, the output path is generated from the first input
file as \fISTEM\fB-collage.\fIEXT\fR.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-H
Stitch images horizontally.
.TP
.B \-o \fIOUTPUT\fR
Write the collage to \fIOUTPUT\fR.
.TP
.B \-V
Stitch images vertically. This is the default.
.TP
.B \-h
Show usage help.
.TP
.B \-v, --version
Show the plugin name and version.
.SH OUTPUT
The command prints the output file path and reports it through
\fBimgmod_output\fR so it can be optimized by \fBimgmod -O\fR.
.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.B magick
ImageMagick command used to inspect and transform images.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Create a vertical collage:
.nf
.B imgmod collage first.png second.png
.fi
.TP
Create a horizontal collage from a directory:
.nf
.B imgmod collage -H -o joined.png images/
.fi
